### Description

I have an Angular 18 service that would update a `BehaviorSubject` once a minute, to track time in the application.  I have unit tests for this, which pass.  When I upgrade to Angualr 19, my tests no longer passed.  It seemed to be an issue with how `tick` works, which I see mentioned in [the release notes here](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md#core-8)

> The timers that are used for zone coalescing and hybrid mode scheduling (which schedules an application state synchronization when changes happen outside the Angular zone) will now run in the zone above Angular rather than the root zone. This will mostly affect tests which use `fakeAsync`: these timers will now be visible to `fakeAsync` and can be affected by `tick` or `flush`.

Here is my service:
```ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class TimerService {
  private isRunningSubject$ = new BehaviorSubject(false);
  private totalDurationMin = 0;
  private totalDurationMinutesSubject$ = new BehaviorSubject(this.totalDurationMin);
  private timerSubscription = new Subscription();

  public totalDurationMinutes$ = this.totalDurationMinutesSubject$.asObservable();
  public isRunning$ = this.isRunningSubject$.asObservable();

  public start(): void {
    this.isRunningSubject$.next(true);
    this.totalDurationMinutesSubject$.next(this.totalDurationMin);

    this.timerSubscription = interval(60 * 1000).subscribe({
      next: () => {
        this.totalDurationMin++;
        this.totalDurationMinutesSubject$.next(this.totalDurationMin);
      },
    });
  }

  public stop(): void {
    this.isRunningSubject$.next(false);
    this.timerSubscription.unsubscribe();
  }
}
```

And here is my unit test which passes in Angular 18, but fails in 19

```ts
it('should update the observables and start the timer', fakeAsync(() => {
  //skip initial emit, the start of the timer, and then then next 4 minute ticks
  service.totalDurationMinutes$.pipe(skip(6)).subscribe({
    next: (val) => {
      console.log(`minutes: ${val}`);
      expect(val).toEqual(5);
    },
  });

  service.start();
  tick(60 * 1000 * 5); //simulate 5 minutes passing

  discardPeriodicTasks();
}));
```

### Please provide a link to a minimal reproduction of the bug

 - [Angular 18](https://stackblitz.com/edit/ng-jasmine-rbkdn2wp?file=src%2Fapp%2Ftimer.service.spec.ts)
 - [Angular 19](https://stackblitz.com/edit/ng-jasmine-rvqhvurf?file=src%2Fapp%2Ftimer.service.spec.ts)

### Please provide the exception or error you saw


The unit test fails with `Expected 6 to equal 5.`

You'll notice that in v18, the console output contains
```
minutes: 5
```
and in v19 it contains
```
minutes: 5
minutes: 6
```


