### Description

I had a use case for linked signal concerning grid. The grid has checkboxes and the logic for them is:
1. When the original data changes - reset all checkboxes to empty array
2. When filtered data changes (there are filters for the grid - free search, columns, etc...) keep the old checkboxes only if they are still in the filtered data.

When I created a linked signal it looked like that:
```ts
checkedItems = linkedSignal<[string[], string[]], string[]>({
  source: () => [this.data(), this.filteredData()],
  computation: ([data, filteredData], previous) => {
    const dataChanged = !previous || data !== previous.source[0]

    if (dataChanged) {
      return []
    }

    return previous.value.filter((checkedItem) => filteredData.includes(checkedItem))
  },
})
``` 
In this case the "change detection" is only for `data` but there are cases where you need to identify more changes - especially if you need state in component dependent on multiple inputs (where `ngOnChanges` was used previously).

### Proposed solution

Add either an overload or another function called `linkedSignalWithChanges` which will work this way:
```ts
checkedItems = linkedSignalWithChanges<[string[], string[]], string[]>({
  source: () => [this.data, this.filteredData],
  computation: ([, filteredData], [dataChange], previousValue) => {
    if (dataChange !== undefined) {
      return []
    }

    return previousValue.filter((checkedItem) => filteredData.includes(checkedItem))
  },
})
```
Source will be array of signals (and not a reactive function)
Computation:
First parameter - source value like now
Second parameter - array of changes (same order as source signals array) - can be an array of `SimpleChange`
Third parameter - previousValue

### Alternatives considered

Keep using the more verbose way using current linked signal.
Create this as a wrapper function in user code.
Maybe I am doing something wrong and there is another way to solve those use cases without "change detecting" and I will be happy to see how.

